\begin_layout Subsection
Heritability Estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Narrow-sense heritability (
\begin_inset Formula $h²$
\end_inset

),
 defined as the proportion of phenotypic variance explained by additive genetic effects 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Campos2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 was estimated for each of the 21 LCH components derived from color traits.
 We used Bayesian Ridge Regression (BRR),
 implemented in the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
texttt{BGLR}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 R package 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Campos2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 because the color-related traits analyzed in this study are expected to follow a polygenic architecture,
 with many loci of small effect contributing additively to the phenotype.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
BRR assumes normally distributed genetic effects across markers and estimates heritability by repeatedly sampling the additive genetic variance (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{a}^{2}$
\end_inset

) and residual variance (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

) through a Bayesian process.
 The model was run for 15,000 iterations,
 with a burn-in of 5,000 and thinning every 5 steps.
 Heritability was computed at each iteration as:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h²=\dfrac{\sigma_{a}^{2}}{\sigma_{a}^{2}+\sigma_{e}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This procedure yields a posterior distribution of heritability values for each trait,
 rather than a single point estimate.
 From this distribution,
 we report the posterior mean and the 95% credible interval.
 Unlike confidence intervals from frequentist methods,
 a Bayesian 95% credible interval indicates the range within which the true 
\begin_inset Formula $h²$
\end_inset

 value lies with 95% probability,
 given the data and model.
\end_layout

